Escape from the Mechanical Bathhouse

A Whimsy

by Nathaniel Spence

Press any key to continue

You knew you shouldn’t have had the extra glass of red wine. You knew you shouldn’t have eaten that cheese. But it had been a tough day at the office, and you just couldn’t help yourself.

You kept reliving it again and again in your head: the smug look Philips gave you as you were summoned to HQ, the frosty reception of silver-haired, steely-eyed Ms Sweetfield, guardian of the outer office, to your feeble attempts at banter while you waited outside the boardroom (just nerves, of course – ordinarily you wouldn’t have dared to try). They kept you waiting for a long time… And then the summons within, to face the Directors: the unholy trinity of Messrs Clarke, Clark and Clerk, presided over by the ancient and venerable Arhchibald Claribald Leclercq, once young and maverick, now ancient and doddering CEO of the company he founded more than 40 years ago on nothing more than (his favourite word): ‘inspiration’.

So, they gave you a dressing down. In fact, they tore strips of you, flayed you alive and left you on the carpet begging for mercy. You thought about quitting – the honourable thing to do – but you were too defeated even for that. So you just crawled out through the highly-polished double doors with your tail between your legs, and slunk shamefully back to your desk. The weather outside was foul, but after a few minutes the sympathetic looks of your colleagues were too much: you had to get away. You left the office and walked nowhere, for hours, along endless empty streets, ending up at  last on a park bench in the pouring rain. By the time you got back to your flat, you were exhausted, freezing cold and wet through. You stripped off, longing for a hot bath, but unable to muster the effort to arrange one – so you just sat in your pyjamas and drowned your sorrows with a bottle of Merlot and an over-ripe camembert (the closest thing to comfort food you could find in your fridge). It was almost two by the time you climbed into bed, your brain furred with red wine and the inside of your mouth greasy with cheese. You’d feel terrible in the morning. But for the moment…for the moment…

Your mind muddied and began to drift as weariness overcame you. The last thing you remembered hearing was the chiming of the old fashioned clock in the living room, an heirloom inherited from your grandmother, calling the hour as you sank downward into a deep sleep...

Press any key to start

The Lobby

The Lobby appears to have been designed with a minimal aesthetic in mind containing, as it does, very little other than empty space and expansive surfaces. Smooth, glass-like walls sweep away from you to meet with other walls at distant corners, or to soar upwards to a presumed ceiling, hovering somewhere invisibly far above. The floor is uncarpeted but warm and the air delicately scented with something floral that you don't quite recognise. The whole is suffused with a soothing, peach coloured glow that seems to emanate evenly from every surface.

You can see a clock and a mechanical man (wearing  a bathrobe).

You can go east.

[Type HELP if you don't know where to start]
> x me

> x me

You see the usual forshortened view of your own body, which feels comfortingly familiar, if nothing else does. You are wearing pyjamas.

> x pyjamas

> x pyjamas

They are your most ancient and best-loved pair of blue-and-white striped cotton pyjamas, faded and bobbled and comfortable as only something that has passed through the wash five thousand times can be.

> x man

> x man

He looks like a stereotypical Greek sophist: old, bald, wrinkled and wise. Intelligent grey eyes stare out from beneath an ancient-looking face, and his enormous bushy eyebrows are as snowy-white as his long, curling beard. The overall effect is quite lifelike, although you can tell by the sheen of the hair and the texture of the skin, that he is artificial. There is a serial number inscribed on his sternum and a small keyhole in the side of his neck.

He is frozen in a peculiar attitude, looking to the heavens with one fist raised upwards and an expression of fury on his face.

      He is wearing                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               a bathrobe.
> x serial number

> x serial number

It's a serial number, embossed into the mechanical man's artificial skin.
> read it

> read it

The number reads "RK MIDI Z" in a futuristic machine-readable font.
> x keyhole

> x keyhole

It's just an ordinary looking keyhole.
> x bathrobe

> x bathrobe

It's a fluffy, white towelling bathrobe, tied by a cord at the waist. It has a single pocket.
> x pocket

> x pocket

It is the archetype of bathrobe pockets.
You take a look inside.

You discover a keyring, which you take.

> x keyring

> x keyring

It's a keyring attached to a thick rubber band.

Attached to it are a brass key and a card.
> x brass key

> x brass key

It's a brass Yale-type key.

> x card

> x card

It's a white plastic card with '◈100' printed on one side, and a magnetic strip on the other.

> x clock

> x clock

It has a distinctive 1970s souvenir quality about it; a fine example of Bavarian tourist kitsch. The hands are filigree in yellow enamel, and there is a small door above the clock face.

> x door

> x door

It is a little door above the clock face, about the size and shape of a stereotypical mouse hole and with a small ledge directly in front. It is finished  with a pair of tiny wooden shutters,
which are closed.

> x hands

> x hands

The hands are of a filigree design, and are finished in bright yellow enamel. They show the time as just a fraction past 1 o'clock.

> x walls

> x walls

The walls are made of the same translucent, glass-like material as the floor and are etched all over with a cogwheel design. Attached to the wall high above is what appears to be a bird's nest.
> x nest

> x nest

It looks like a bird's nest, but you haven't a clue as to what kind of bird it might belong to (ornithology is not your strong point). It appears to be occupied, judging from the shapes you can just make out bobbing around inside, and the curious pipe-like chirping that emanates from within.

> turn hands

> turn hands

You turn the hands of the clock and, as the minute hand passes 12, you hear a sharp click and the doors snap open.

A mechanical cuckoo hops onto the ledge and begins to chirp musically.

> x cuckoo

> x cuckoo

It is a fine mechanical imitation of a cuckoo, hopping about and twitching its head from side to side with lifelike poise. Through the gaps between its metal feathers you catch the occasional glimpse of the clockwork complexity within.

> take cuckoo

> take cuckoo

You quickly snatch the cuckoo from its perch before it has time to hop back inside. It chirps furiously, its metal body writhing in your grip.

The little wooden doors slam shut.

> drop cuckoo

> drop cuckoo

With a resentful twitter, the cuckoo flutter from your grasp and flies off in the direction of the nest.

Frantic, discordant chirping noises clash with the familiar twittering of the the cuckoo from somewhere far above: the ornithological equivalent of voices raised in anger.
> z

> z

Time passes.
Angry bird sounds echo about the room. From where you stand, far below, the nest appears to be vibrating...
> z

> z

Time passes.
A frantic scuffle breaks out high above your head, small twigs and other debris raining down as the nest is shaken and the sound of angry birdsong become almost deafening.

You can make out the silhouette of something struggling desperately as it is pushed towards the edge of the nest. Suddenly, a small shape tumbles over the precipice...and hits the floor a few seconds later, with a ringing crash of metal.
> look

> look

The Lobby

The Lobby appears to have been designed with a minimal aesthetic in mind containing, as it does, very little other than empty space and expansive surfaces. Smooth, glass-like walls sweep away from you to meet with other walls at distant corners, or to soar upwards to a presumed ceiling, hovering somewhere invisibly far above. The floor is uncarpeted but warm and the air delicately scented with something floral that you don't quite recognise. The whole is suffused with a soothing, peach coloured glow that seems to emanate evenly from every surface.

You can see a clock, a mechanical man (wearing  a bathrobe) and a broken chick.

You can go east.

> x broken chick

> x broken chick

It's the remains of a mechanical chick, just a few days old. A sorry heap of tiny cogs, ratchets and springs, all exquisitely machined to run smoothly together: once a miraculous mechanism, now a heap of scrap. Such is life.

> search chick

> search chick

You gingerly pick your way through the once-animate heap of clockwork and discover a silver key, which you take.
> x silver key

> x silver key

It is a flat, wide key with a square aperture. It looks like the sort your grandmother used to keep on the mantlepiece, to wind the clock.
> insert silver key

> insert silver key

You insert the key into the mechanical man's neck.
> turn silver key

> turn silver key

You turn the key and hear the nostalgic sound of a clockwork mechanism tightening. Careful not to overwind, you stop after a few turns and take a step back. The key turns in the mechanism as the mechanical man slowly grinds back to life.

"Damn magpies!" he wheezes, his voice whistling like an old pipe organ with faulty valves. He shakes his fist at the nest high above.

The mechanical man shuffles around slowly, his every move accompanied by a dry squeal of metal against metal. "Oh heavens, my aching joints!" he says, as he hobbles about.
> e

> e

The Changing Room

The changing room, a functional space, has all it needs to fulfil its principle role in life as a gatehouse between the outer region of the lobby and the inner sanctum of the bathhouse.

Furnished only with a set of plain metal lockers and an ever vigilant attendant, perpetually on duty, it is as warm, clean and soothingly lit as any of the other of the rooms in this place. There is a doorway to the east, and a cubicle to the north.

You can see the Attendant.

You can go north, east or west.

The attendant eyes you suspiciously...
> x attendant

> x attendant

The attendant is thin, taut and bendy as willow switch. She seems to vibrate faintly with implied menace even as she stands quite still and watches you intently, with her beady eyes. Perhaps it is because you are manifestly out of place amongst her usual clientele, or maybe she just doesn't like the cut of your pyjamas. Either way, she's probably just waiting for the first excuse to escort you off the premises.

She wears a white sleeveless blouse and bloomers, and a white cap jammed down over close-cropped steel grey hair, the whole embroidered all over with a cogwheel design in only fractionally less white white, rendering it nearly invisible to your eyes (but perhaps mechanical people see differently?). You assume that this outfit, so redolent of fashionable high school gym wear of the 1950s, is the standard uniform for bathhouse functionaries.

The mechanical man is here, creaking and rattling around.

"Oh dear me, my aching joints!", he says.

The attendant eyes you suspiciously...
> x lockers

> x lockers

They are just ordinary changing room lockers: metal boxes with hinged doors. There are four lockers in all. Three are open, and the fourth is closed.

"I really must take an oil bath", says the mechanical man. "I'm rusted almost solid! If I wind down now, I may never move again…"

The mechanical man wanders west.

The attendant eyes you suspiciously...
> e

> e

With frightening speed, the attendant springs forwards and intercepts you before you reach the doorway. "Bathers must be appropriately attired!" she practically shouts at you.

The attendant eyes you suspiciously...
